), which comprises nine closely related Palaearctic species associated with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Shinohara &amp; Hara" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[785,849,1845,1871]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[785,849,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Alnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[907,980,1845,1871]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[907,980,1845,1871]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In our molecular study (
<figureCitation box="[1273,1431,1845,1872]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 148" captionStart-1="FIGURE 149" captionStart-2="FIGURE 150" captionStart-3="FIGURE 151" captionStartId-0="235.[151,250,1827,1851]" captionStartId-1="236.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionStartId-2="237.[151,250,1809,1833]" captionStartId-3="238.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox-0="[157,1427,198,1794]" captionTargetBox-1="[169,1416,198,1910]" captionTargetBox-2="[157,1430,185,1782]" captionTargetBox-3="[163,1422,186,1916]" captionTargetId-0="figure-19@235.[151,1436,181,1803]" captionTargetId-1="figure-26@236.[163,1425,181,1919]" captionTargetId-2="figure-19@237.[151,1436,181,1785]" captionTargetId-3="figure-26@238.[157,1430,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId-0="235" captionTargetPageId-1="236" captionTargetPageId-2="237" captionTargetPageId-3="238" captionText-0="FIGURE 148. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 1." captionText-1="FIGURE 149. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 2." captionText-2="FIGURE 150. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 3." captionText-3="FIGURE 151. Condensed ML tree based on CO1 gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 4." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Figs 148–151</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,195,1881,1907]" captionStart="FIGURE 160" captionStartId="245.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[177,1406,188,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@245.[171,1416,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="245" captionText="FIGURE 160. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 1." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">160</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[208,253,1881,1907]" captionStart="FIGURE 161" captionStartId="246.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[177,1403,189,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-26@246.[171,1417,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="246" captionText="FIGURE 161. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 2." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">161</figureCitation>
), the relationships of this group of species were poorly resolved. In the NaK analysis (
<figureCitation box="[1233,1331,1881,1907]" captionStart="FIGURE 160" captionStartId="245.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[177,1406,188,1910]" captionTargetId="figure-19@245.[171,1416,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="245" captionText="FIGURE 160. Condensed ML tree based on NaK gene sequences, with details of Pamphilius vafer group, part 1." pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Fig. 160</figureCitation>
), the 
<specimenCount pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara" authorityYear="2005" box="[305,439,1917,1943]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alnivorus">
<emphasis box="[305,439,1917,1943]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">P. alnivorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[507,571,1917,1943]" name="Japan" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Japan</collectingCountry>
did not even form a clade.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1437,1521,2016]" lastBlockId="85.[151,1436,150,249]" lastPageId="85" lastPageNumber="86" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara" authorityYear="2005" box="[199,441,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alnivorus">
<emphasis box="[199,441,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Pamphilius alnivorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closest to 
<taxonomicName authority="Takeuchi, 1930" authorityName="Takeuchi" authorityYear="1930" box="[592,930,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nakagawai">
<emphasis box="[592,744,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">P. nakagawai</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Takeuchi, K." box="[753,930,1953,1979]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" pagination="3 - 16" refId="ref80368" refString="Takeuchi, K. (1930) A revisional list of the Japanese Pamphiliidae, with description of nine new species. Transactions of the Kansai Entomological Society, 1, 3 - 16." type="journal article" year="1930">Takeuchi, 1930</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, occurring in Honshu, Shikoku and Kyushu, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,218,1989,2015]" name="Japan" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Japan</collectingCountry>
, in morphology and bionomics (Shinohara 2005). The larva of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shinohara" authorityYear="2005" box="[931,1065,1989,2015]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alnivorus">
<emphasis box="[931,1065,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">P. alnivorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a solitary leaf-roller on 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Shinohara &amp; Hara" baseAuthorityYear="1993" box="[1365,1429,1989,2015]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1365,1429,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Alnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, making a leaf-roll on the underside but oviposition is on the upperside (
<typeStatus box="[980,1037,151,177]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Type</typeStatus>
II of Shinohara 2005). The site of oviposition (upperside of a leaf) and direction of leaf-rolling (underside) in this species are quite peculiar, otherwise known only for the 
<taxonomicName box="[372,445,223,249]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fagales" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[372,445,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-feeding species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Shinohara 2005)" baseAuthorityName="Shinohara" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[640,962,222,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphiliidae" genus="Pamphilius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallipes">
<emphasis box="[640,757,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">P. pallipes</emphasis>
(Shinohara 2005)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
